<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-logarithmic-functions">
  <title>Logarithmic functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use inverse relationships to understand how logarithms and exponentials change.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Differentiate expressions involving real exponents, other bases, and logarithmic combinations.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Apply logarithmic differentiation and relative rates to analyze more complex models.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Since <m>\ln x</m> and <m>\ee^{x}</m> are inverses, we can evaluate <m>\DS\dv{x} \ee^{\ln x}</m> two ways to find that <m>\DS\dv{x}\ln x=\frac{1}{x}</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        In general, derivatives of inverse functions:
        <me>
          \dv{x} f\inv(x)=\dfrac1{f'(f\inv(x))}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Logarithmic differentiation:
        <me>
          \dd(\ln y) = \frac{\dd{y}}{y}
        </me>
        Good for complicated derivatives or derivatives involving exponents.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Reminder of logarithm rules as opposites of exponent rules:
        <md>
          <mrow>\ln(uv) \amp = \ln u + \ln v</mrow>
          <mrow>\ln\left(\frac{u}{v}\right) \amp = \ln u - \ln v</mrow>
          <mrow>\ln(u^r) \amp = r \ln u</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Differentiating <m>x^r</m> for any real exponent <m>r</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>y \amp = x^r </mrow>
          <mrow>\ln y \amp = r \ln x </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd(\ln y) \amp = \dd(r \ln x) </mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{y}\dd{y} \amp = r \frac{1}{x} \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd{y} \amp = r x^{r-1} \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dv{y}{x} \amp = r x^{r-1} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Differentiating <m>b^x</m> for any base <m>b>0</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>y \amp = b^x </mrow>
          <mrow>\ln y \amp = x \ln b </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd(\ln y) \amp = \dd(x \ln b) </mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{y}\dd{y} \amp = \ln b \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd{y} \amp = y \ln b \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dv{y}{x} \amp = b^x \ln b </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Differentiating <m>\log_b{x}</m> for any base <m>b>0</m>:
        <md>
          <mrow>y \amp = \log_b{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>b^y \amp = x </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd(b^y) \amp = \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>b^y \ln b \dd{y} \amp = \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dd{y} \amp = \frac{1}{x \ln b} \dd{x} </mrow>
          <mrow>\dv{y}{x} \amp = \frac{1}{x \ln b} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Elasticity of a function:
        <aside>
          <p>
            The elasticity of a power function is its degree, and in the limit, the elasticity of a polynomial is its degree.
            This can in some sense be used to define the degree of non-power functions.
          </p>
        </aside>
        <me>
          E=\dv{(\ln y)}{(\ln x)}=\frac{x}{y}\dv{y}{x}=\frac{\dd{y}/\dd{x}}{y/x}
        </me>
        This is a relative rate of change, which is useful in economics (e.g.
        price elasticity of demand).
        Maybe use this as the guiding application?
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
